#Text=Baldassare Donato
#Text=Baldassare Donato
#Text=( also Donati ) ( 1525-1530 – June 1603 ) was an Italian composer and singer of the Venetian school of the late Renaissance .

#Text=He was maestro di cappella of the prestigious St. Mark 's Basilica at the end of the 16th century , and was an important figure in the development of Italian light secular music , especially the villanella .
#Text=Life
#Text=Details of his early life are unavailable ; it is not even known where he was born .
#Text=The first record of Donato is as a singer at St. Mark 's in Venice in 1550 , and he was given charge of the musical training of the boys there in 1562 .

#Text=When Gioseffo Zarlino took over the post of maestro di cappella from Cipriano de Rore in 1565 , Donato was demoted back to being a singer ; conflict between the two men seems to have been a feature of life at St. Mark 's , culminating in a climactic fight in 1569 , publicly and scandalously , during the Feast of St. Mark .

#Text=In 1577 Donato took a position at the Scuola Grande di S Rocco , another Venetian church with an impressive musical tradition and substantial performing ensemble ; however he failed to get along with his employers there as well , resigning by 1580 .

#Text=In 1588 he became assistant maestro di cappella at St. Mark 's , while Zarlino was still alive ( whether because of reconcilement or politics is not clear ) , and in 1590 he took over the post of his former antagonist , holding it until his death in 1603 .
#Text=Music and influence

#Text=Donato represented a progressive trend in the Venetian school , which was already a progressive tradition compared to the other major contemporary Italian musical styles ( especially as compared to the Roman School ) .

#Text=The progressive trend in the Venetian school was represented by composers such as Donato , Giovanni Croce , and Andrea and Giovanni Gabrieli ; the conservative trend involved composers and theorists such as Zarlino , Cipriano de Rore , and Claudio Merulo , who tended to follow the Franco-Flemish style which was predominant almost everywhere else in Europe until after mid-century .
#Text=Donato 's sacred music is the most conservative portion of his output , usually using polyphony in the Palestrina style , but also using some of the grand polychoral effects of the Gabrielis .

#Text=In spite of his evident disdain for Zarlino 's conservatism , he clearly absorbed some of his style and teaching , as can be seen in his smooth mastery of counterpoint and Zarlinoesque use of dissonance , at least when he was deliberately composing in the Franco-Flemish style .
#Text=Probably his greatest significance to music history is in the development of a light secular form known as the villanella , a lighter form of madrigal , of Neapolitan origin .
#Text=Some of these pieces may have been intended for dancing , and they were evidently popular .

#Text=They are similar to the French chanson , often have a memorable melody in the topmost part , contain vigorous cross-rhythms , and avoid the polyphonic and chromatic complexity of the mid-century madrigal .
#Text=Donato also wrote madrigals in a more serious style , as well as psalm settings , motets , and ceremonial music .
